\begin_layout Section
Financial Feasibility
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Financial feasibility study analyses the total costs of a proposed project
 (including all development costs and operating costs) and the potential
 revenues that the project can generate.
 Generally if the potential revenues of the proposed project can cover all
 of the costs, then the project is deemed to be financially feasible.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For our project we don't need specialized hardware, the requirements are
 satisfied by the laptops of the team members and the workstations provided
 by the college.
 And in case of software we plan to use only open source software which
 is readily available on the internet.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By analyzing the current scenario we contemplate that the project would
 entail 1200 person-hours of effort assuming each team member works 10 hours
 a week for 12 weeks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hence our project is financially feasible.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Cost Benefit Analysis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An evaluation of development cost against the ultimate income or benefits
 derived from the developed system.
 If the benefits outweigh the costs, then the decision is made to design
