\begin_layout Section
Technical Feasibility
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is frequently the most difficult area to access at this stage of the
 system development process.
 It involves the study of functions, performance, & constraints that may
 affect the ability to achieve an acceptable system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This study reveals whether reliable hardware and software, technical resources
 capable of meeting the needs of a proposed system can be acquired or developed
 by an organization in the required time.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The project is technically feasible during the development process as all
 the software which we intend to use is open source, and easy to operate
 by the all the members of the development team.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The technology we intend to use is readily available and easily realizable.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The finished product will also be technically feasible as it can be run
 on normal computers as well as servers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Advances in operating system performance, multi-threading and event based
 I/O means that decent performance can be achieved even on commodity hardware.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Experts have already designed appropriate interfaces for various languages
 to interact with web servers and many frameworks exist which simplify some
 tasks.
 So we will not have to start from scratch on all fronts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the other hand, these might be technological downsides:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Server overload can lead to the complete failure of the service since it
 runs on a single server and so has no fault tolerance.
 This can be countered by disallowing new connections over a certain threshold,
 but this would affect customer experience.
 This will require trade-offs further in the planning and development process.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The performance of the product on the user side heavily depends on the quality
 of the connection.
 This can be mitigated by offering options to stream at lower quality.
\end_layout

